as my mother would say.

499
00:36:37,361 --> 00:36:40,697
- Did he ever make a pass at you?
- No.

500
00:36:41,866 --> 00:36:45,160
No, Dr. Sheehan's a good doctor,
he would never...

501
00:36:48,539 --> 00:36:50,832
Could I have a glass of water, please?

502
00:36:50,916 --> 00:36:52,333
No problem.

503
00:37:07,183 --> 00:37:09,517
- Thank you, Marshal.
- Sure.

504
00:37:13,230 --> 00:37:16,608
I just have one more question for you,
Mrs. Kearns.

505
00:37:19,862 --> 00:37:23,156
Did you ever meet a patient
named Andrew Laeddis?

506
00:37:26,243 --> 00:37:27,410
No.

507
00:37:28,788 --> 00:37:30,622
Never heard of him.

508
00:37:36,378 --> 00:37:37,545
She was coached.

509
00:37:38,130 --> 00:37:40,715
She used practically the same words
as Cawley and the nurse,

510
00:37:40,800 --> 00:37:42,300
like she'd been told exactly what to say.

511
00:37:42,384 --> 00:37:44,219
Who's Andrew Laeddis?

512
00:37:48,808 --> 00:37:53,144
You asked every one of those patients
back there about him. Who is he?

513
00:37:56,982 --> 00:38:00,443
What the hell, boss?
I'm your partner, for Christ's sake.

514
00:38:00,528 --> 00:38:02,403
We just met, Chuck.

515
00:38:02,822 --> 00:38:06,407
You've been on the beat for a long time.
You've got a duty. You've got a career.

516
00:38:06,492 --> 00:38:10,912
What I'm doing,
it's not exactly by the book.

517
00:38:12,331 --> 00:38:15,124
I don't give a damn
about by-the-book, boss.

518
00:38:15,209 --> 00:38:18,086
I just wanna know
what the hell's going on.

519
00:38:22,341 --> 00:38:24,968
When this case came over the wires,

520
00:38:25,845 --> 00:38:28,847
I requested it specifically,
you understand?

521
00:38:29,265 --> 00:38:30,473
Why?

522
00:38:32,726 --> 00:38:34,435
Andrew Laeddis,

523
00:38:35,271 --> 00:38:37,438
he was the maintenance man
in the apartment building

524
00:38:37,523 --> 00:38:39,691
where my wife and I lived.

525
00:38:40,734 --> 00:38:41,985
Okay.

526
00:38:43,821 --> 00:38:45,864
He was also a firebug.

527
00:38:48,659 --> 00:38:51,286
Andrew Laeddis lit the match

528
00:38:54,039 --> 00:38:56,958
that caused the fire that killed my wife.

529
00:39:05,175 --> 00:39:06,634
Let them out!

530
00:39:09,305 --> 00:39:12,640
- What happened to Laeddis?
- He got away with it.

531
00:39:12,725 --> 00:39:15,143
Laeddis got away with it
and then he disappeared.

532
00:39:15,227 --> 00:39:18,229
About a year ago, I open up the paper
and there he is.

533
00:39:18,314 --> 00:39:22,817
Ugly-looking son of a bitch. Huge scar
from his right temple down to his left lip.

534
00:39:22,902 --> 00:39:26,362
Eyes different colors.
Not the type of face you'd forget.

535
00:39:26,447 --> 00:39:29,574
He burned down a schoolhouse,
killed two people,

536
00:39:29,658 --> 00:39:31,409
said voices told him to do it.

537
00:39:31,493 --> 00:39:34,120
First he went to prison,
then he got transferred here.

538
00:39:34,204 --> 00:39:36,414
- Then what?
- Then nothing.

539
00:39:36,498 --> 00:39:40,251
He vanished like he never existed.
No record whatsoever.

540
00:39:40,336 --> 00:39:42,712
Pretty sure he's not in Ward B.
That leaves Ward C.

541
00:39:42,796 --> 00:39:44,088
Or he could be dead.

542
00:39:44,173 --> 00:39:46,758
So could Rachel Solando,
for that matter.

543
00:39:46,842 --> 00:39:49,427
Lot of places to hide a body here.

544
00:39:50,220 --> 00:39:53,139
Only one place
no one would really notice.

545
00:40:04,693 --> 00:40:08,780
That patient, Bridget Kearns,
when she sent me for water,

546
00:40:08,864 --> 00:40:11,783
she said something to you back there,
didn't she?

547
00:40:11,867 --> 00:40:12,992
No.

548
00:40:14,912 --> 00:40:16,204
Come on, boss.

549
00:40:20,084 --> 00:40:21,626
She wrote it.

550
00:40:37,059 --> 00:40:38,226
Boss!

551
00:40:38,560 --> 00:40:42,146
We gotta get indoors. It's turning
into a fucking Kansas out here.

552
00:40:42,231 --> 00:40:44,482
- Hold on.
- No, let's go!

553
00:40:47,361 --> 00:40:48,820
Watch out!

554
00:40:50,906 --> 00:40:52,156
Jesus!

555
00:40:53,909 --> 00:40:56,202
- Come on! Up there!
- Let's go!

556
00:40:58,872 --> 00:41:00,832
Get in there! Let's go!

557
00:41:04,461 --> 00:41:05,670
Boss!

558
00:41:12,761 --> 00:41:14,804
- God!
- Jesus Christ!

559
00:41:16,140 --> 00:41:18,099
Damn it. God!

560
00:41:26,775 --> 00:41:30,069
- You okay, boss?
- Yeah, I'm all right.

561
00:41:37,077 --> 00:41:41,330
So if Laeddis is here,
what are you gonna do about it?

562
00:41:44,376 --> 00:41:46,669
I'm not here to kill Laeddis.

563
00:41:54,344 --> 00:41:56,095
If it was my wife, I'd kill him.

564
00:41:56,180 --> 00:41:57,180
Twice.

565
00:42:07,941 --> 00:42:12,570
When we got through the gates
at Dachau, the SS guards surrendered.

566
00:42:21,163 --> 00:42:26,834
The Kommandant tried to kill himself
before we got there, but he...

567
00:42:28,003 --> 00:42:29,295
He botched it.

568
00:42:30,839 --> 00:42:32,840
Took him an hour to die.

569
00:42:38,013 --> 00:42:41,682
When I went outside,
I saw all the bodies on the ground.

570
00:42:46,146 --> 00:42:47,855
Too many to count.

571
00:43:14,550 --> 00:43:16,384
Too many to imagine.

572
00:43:19,012 --> 00:43:20,721
So, yeah, the...

573
00:43:22,891 --> 00:43:24,809
The guards surrendered,
we took their guns,

574
00:43:24,893 --> 00:43:26,811
and we lined them up.

575
00:44:11,023 --> 00:44:13,149
It wasn't warfare. It was...

576
00:44:15,194 --> 00:44:16,694
It was murder.

577
00:44:20,199 --> 00:44:23,117
Yeah, I've had enough of killing.

578
00:44:25,621 --> 00:44:27,622
That's not why I'm here.

579
00:44:28,665 --> 00:44:30,708
So what is this all about?

580
00:44:32,753 --> 00:44:38,633
After Laeddis vanished, I started doing
some checking on Ashecliffe.

581
00:44:40,135 --> 00:44:43,221
A lot of people know about this place,
but no one wants to talk.

582
00:44:43,305 --> 00:44:47,266
You know, it's like it...
It's like they're scared or something.

583
00:44:49,311 --> 00:44:52,396
You know, this place is funded
by a special grant

584
00:44:53,315 --> 00:44:56,150
from The House
Un-American Activities Committee?

585
00:44:56,235 --> 00:44:59,403
HUAC? And how exactly
are we fighting the communists

586
00:44:59,488 --> 00:45:01,822
from an island in Boston Harbor?

587
00:45:02,449 --> 00:45:05,076
By conducting experiments on the mind.

588
00:45:06,495 --> 00:45:07,954
At least that's my guess.

589
00:45:08,038 --> 00:45:09,747
And you think that's going on here?

590
00:45:09,831 --> 00:45:12,333
Like I said, no one would talk, right?

591
00:45:12,417 --> 00:45:15,086
Till I found somebody
who used to be a patient here.

592
00:45:15,170 --> 00:45:19,548
Guy's name is George Noyce.
Nice college kid. Socialist.

593
00:45:19,633 --> 00:45:21,676
He gets offered some money
to do a psych study.

594
00:45:21,760 --> 00:45:23,135
Guess what they were testing?

595
00:45:23,220 --> 00:45:24,303
Toothpaste.

596
00:45:24,388 --> 00:45:26,764
So, he starts
seeing dragons everywhere.

597
00:45:26,848 --> 00:45:31,852
He almost beats his professor to death.
Ends up here in Ashecliffe, Ward C.

598
00:45:32,521 --> 00:45:35,982
They release him after one year, right?
And what does he do?

599
00:45:36,066 --> 00:45:40,987
Two weeks on the mainland, he walks
into a bar, stabs three men to death.

600
00:45:41,780 --> 00:45:46,492
His lawyer pleads insanity, but Noyce,
he stands up in the courtroom and he...

601
00:45:46,576 --> 00:45:51,038
He begs the judge for the electric chair.
Anywhere but a mental hospital.

602
00:45:51,665 --> 00:45:54,250
Judge gives him life in Dedham Prison.

603
00:45:55,294 --> 00:45:56,335
And you found him.

604
00:45:56,420 --> 00:45:58,087
Yeah, I found him.

605
00:45:58,171 --> 00:46:00,673
Well, he's a mess.

606
00:46:02,259 --> 00:46:04,385
But it's pretty clear
from what he tells me.

607
00:46:04,469 --> 00:46:05,594
What?

608
00:46:05,679 --> 00:46:08,431
They're experimenting on people here.

609
00:46:08,515 --> 00:46:10,224
I don't know, boss.

610
00:46:11,518 --> 00:46:13,019
How do you believe a crazy guy?

611
00:46:13,103 --> 00:46:14,770
That's the beauty of it, isn't it?

612
00:46:14,855 --> 00:46:19,108
Crazy people, they're the perfect
subjects. They talk, nobody listens.

613
00:46:19,693 --> 00:46:21,360
I stood at Dachau.

614
00:46:21,611 --> 00:46:26,282
We saw what human beings are
capable of doing to each other, right?

615
00:46:26,366 --> 00:46:28,951
For Christ's sakes, we fought
a goddamn war to stop them,

616
00:46:29,036 --> 00:46:32,788
and now... Now I find out it may be
happening here? On our soil?

617
00:46:32,873 --> 00:46:33,914
No.

618
00:46:35,083 --> 00:46:37,710
So what are you really here to do, Ted?

619
00:46:38,420 --> 00:46:42,214
I'm gonna get the proof,
I'm gonna go back,

620
00:46:42,299 --> 00:46:45,968
and I'm gonna blow the lid off this place.
That's it.

621
00:46:47,387 --> 00:46:48,888
Wait a minute.

622
00:46:49,473 --> 00:46:52,266
You started asking around
about Ashecliffe,

623
00:46:52,351 --> 00:46:53,768
waiting for a chance to get out here,

624
00:46:53,852 --> 00:46:56,437
and then suddenly
they need a U.S. Marshal?

625
00:46:56,521 --> 00:47:00,399
Yeah, I got lucky. There was a patient
escape. It was the perfect excuse.

626
00:47:00,484 --> 00:47:03,486
No, no, no, boss.
Luck doesn't work that way.

627
00:47:03,570 --> 00:47:05,237
The world doesn't work that way.

628
00:47:05,322 --> 00:47:08,616
They got an electrified fence
around a septic facility.

629
00:47:08,700 --> 00:47:11,827
Ward C is inside a Civil War fort?

630
00:47:11,912 --> 00:47:15,581
A Chief of Staff with ties to the OSS?
Funding from HUAC?

631
00:47:15,665 --> 00:47:20,252
I mean, Jesus Christ, everything about
this place stinks of government ops.

632
00:47:20,337 --> 00:47:21,712
What if they wanted you here?

633
00:47:21,797 --> 00:47:23,672
- Bullshit.
- You were asking questions.

634
00:47:23,757 --> 00:47:24,799
- Bullshit! Bullshit!
- Bullshit.

635
00:47:24,883 --> 00:47:26,133
We came here for Rachel Solando.

636
00:47:26,218 --> 00:47:29,095
Where's one shred of evidence
she even existed?

637
00:47:29,179 --> 00:47:30,346
There's no way they could've known

638
00:47:30,430 --> 00:47:31,806
I'd be assigned to this case.
There's no way.

639
00:47:31,890 --> 00:47:35,226
What if while you were looking into
them, they were looking into you?

640
00:47:35,310 --> 00:47:38,521
All they had to do was fake an escape
to get you here, and now they have you.

641
00:47:38,605 --> 00:47:40,398
Now they have us both. Here! Now!

642
00:47:44,653 --> 00:47:48,989
Marshals, are you out here?
This is Deputy Warden McPherson.

643
00:47:50,117 --> 00:47:51,158
Marshals!

644
00:47:51,243 --> 00:47:53,244
How about that? They found us, huh?

645
00:47:53,328 --> 00:47:55,830
It's an island, boss.
They're always gonna find us.

646
00:47:57,207 --> 00:47:58,833
I know you're in there.

647
00:48:00,419 --> 00:48:03,921
We're getting off this goddamn island.
You and me. Come on.

648
00:48:08,301 --> 00:48:10,010
- Come on!
- Go, go!

649
00:48:19,813 --> 00:48:22,940
Get dried off.
Dr. Cawley wants to talk to you now.

650
00:48:23,567 --> 00:48:27,111
And hurry up! This thing is turning
into a goddamn hurricane!

651
00:48:32,284 --> 00:48:36,203
I dropped those suits off to be cleaned.
Should be ready by tomorrow.

652
00:48:36,705 --> 00:48:39,498
That is, if we all don't wash away first.

653
00:48:39,583 --> 00:48:44,044
You know, speaking of which, I'm afraid
your smokes are pretty much done for.

654
00:48:44,629 --> 00:48:45,796
So...

655
00:48:47,466 --> 00:48:49,592
This is our only choice, huh?

656
00:48:49,676 --> 00:48:52,720
Got something really nice in
a prison gray if that don't work for you.

657
00:48:52,804 --> 00:48:55,723
Now that you mention it,
these are just fine.

658
00:48:56,433 --> 00:48:58,058
That's why I must repeat my insistence

659
00:48:58,143 --> 00:49:01,270
that all Ward C patients
be placed in manual restraints.

660
00:49:01,938 --> 00:49:05,274
If the facility floods, they'll drown.
You know that.

661
00:49:05,734 --> 00:49:06,984
That would take a lot of flooding.

662
00:49:07,068 --> 00:49:09,737
We're on an island in the middle
of the ocean during a hurricane.

663
00:49:09,821 --> 00:49:12,490
A lot of flooding seems like
a distinct possibility.

664
00:49:12,574 --> 00:49:14,909
It's a gamble, Stephen.
Say the power fails.

665
00:49:14,993 --> 00:49:16,243
There's a backup generator.

666
00:49:16,328 --> 00:49:19,038
And if that goes,
the cell doors will open.

667
00:49:20,582 --> 00:49:22,249
Where are they going to go?

668
00:49:22,918 --> 00:49:25,920
They can't just hop a ferry, scoot over
to the mainland and wreak havoc.

669
00:49:26,004 --> 00:49:27,004
Oh, you're quite right.

670
00:49:27,088 --> 00:49:30,257
They're far more likely
to wreak havoc right here on us.

671
00:49:31,176 --> 00:49:34,094
If they're manacled to the floor,
they'll die.

672
00:49:34,429 --> 00:49:36,305
This is 24 human beings.

673
00:49:36,932 --> 00:49:38,265
And you can live with that, can you?

674
00:49:38,433 --> 00:49:40,434
Well, frankly, if it were up to me,

675
00:49:40,519 --> 00:49:43,854
I'd put all 42 in Wards A and B
in manual restraints as well.

676
00:49:43,939 --> 00:49:46,815
- Excuse me! Excuse me.
- Marshal.

677
00:49:46,900 --> 00:49:49,443
I'm sorry, Doctor.
I just have one quick question.

678
00:49:49,528 --> 00:49:50,736
Yes, I'll be with you in a moment.

679
00:49:50,820 --> 00:49:53,822
When we spoke this morning
about Rachel Solando's note...

680
00:49:53,907 --> 00:49:55,616
"The law of four." I love that.

681
00:49:55,700 --> 00:49:59,245
...you said you had no idea what that
second line could refer to, correct?

682
00:50:00,413 --> 00:50:04,750
"Who is 67?" Yes, I'm afraid I still don't.
None of us do.

683
00:50:06,169 --> 00:50:07,419
Nothing comes to mind?

684
00:50:10,131 --> 00:50:11,340
Nothing?

685
00:50:15,303 --> 00:50:20,349
Because I believe I just heard you say
there are 24 patients in Ward C

686
00:50:20,433 --> 00:50:22,893
and 42 patients in Wards A and B,

687
00:50:22,978 --> 00:50:26,438
which means there's a total of,
what, 66 patients at this facility?

688
00:50:28,108 --> 00:50:29,108
That is correct, yes.

689
00:50:32,571 --> 00:50:35,656
Well, it seems to me
Rachel Solando was suggesting

690
00:50:35,740 --> 00:50:38,867
that you have a 67th patient, Doctor.

691
00:50:40,453 --> 00:50:41,954
But I'm afraid we don't.

692
00:50:42,497 --> 00:50:44,415
This is ridiculous.
What are they doing here?

693
00:50:44,499 --> 00:50:46,667
We're doing our goddamn job.

694
00:50:47,002 --> 00:50:49,670
Didn't McPherson tell you
the good news?

695
00:50:50,839 --> 00:50:53,257
No. What's the good news, Doctor?

696
00:50:53,341 --> 00:50:55,092
Rachel's been found.

697
00:50:56,136 --> 00:50:57,511
She's here.

698
00:50:58,680 --> 00:51:00,180
Safe and sound.

699
00:51:11,860 --> 00:51:13,902
There's not a mark on her.

700
00:51:17,532 --> 00:51:18,949
Who are these men?

701
00:51:22,329 --> 00:51:23,912
Why are they in my house?

702
00:51:23,997 --> 00:51:28,500
Police officers, Rachel.
They have a few questions.

703
00:51:32,047 --> 00:51:33,213
Ma'am.

704
00:51:36,593 --> 00:51:41,180
There has been a sighting of a known
communist subversive in this area,

705
00:51:41,264 --> 00:51:43,182
passing out literature.

706
00:51:44,976 --> 00:51:46,185
Here?

707
00:51:48,396 --> 00:51:50,022
In this neighborhood?

708
00:51:50,106 --> 00:51:51,857
Yes, I'm afraid so.

709
00:51:53,234 --> 00:51:56,820
Now if you could tell us what you did
yesterday, where you were,

710
00:51:56,905 --> 00:51:59,031
it would really help us
narrow down our search.

711
00:52:00,700 --> 00:52:01,909
Yes...

712
00:52:04,663 --> 00:52:05,996
Well, I...

713
00:52:08,917 --> 00:52:11,752
I made breakfast
for Jim and the children,

714
00:52:13,421 --> 00:52:14,838
and then I

715
00:52:16,716 --> 00:52:18,926
packed Jim's lunch and he left.

716
00:52:22,597 --> 00:52:25,265
Then I sent the children off to school.

717
00:52:29,688 --> 00:52:30,938
And then

718
00:52:37,362 --> 00:52:40,406
I decided to take a long swim
in the lake.

719
00:52:47,288 --> 00:52:48,497
I see.

720
00:52:52,210 --> 00:52:53,752
And after that?

721
00:53:01,928 --> 00:53:03,262
After that,

722
00:53:13,064 --> 00:53:14,690
I thought of you.

723
00:53:20,697 --> 00:53:24,658
I'm sorry, ma'am,
I don't know what you're talking about.

724
00:53:27,662 --> 00:53:30,622
Don't you know how lonely
I've been, Jim?

725
00:53:36,588 --> 00:53:37,671
You're gone.

726
00:53:41,926 --> 00:53:43,385
You're dead.

727
00:53:48,433 --> 00:53:50,309
I cry every night.

728
00:53:56,316 --> 00:53:58,525
How am I supposed to survive?

729
00:54:00,028 --> 00:54:01,195
God.

730
00:54:11,581 --> 00:54:14,875
Rachel, it'll be all right.

731
00:54:18,129 --> 00:54:20,172
I'm so sorry, but every...

732
00:54:21,883 --> 00:54:24,718
Everything's gonna be all right. Okay?

733
00:54:26,638 --> 00:54:28,096
I buried you.

734
00:54:30,433 --> 00:54:33,060
I buried an empty casket.
Your body rained down,

735
00:54:33,144 --> 00:54:36,647
lumps of flesh splashing into the sea,
eaten by sharks.

736
00:54:40,902 --> 00:54:43,529
My Jim's dead,
so who the fuck are you?

737
00:54:46,950 --> 00:54:48,617
Who the fuck are you?

738
00:54:49,369 --> 00:54:50,494
- Who are you?
- Hey, hey, hey, hey.

739
00:54:50,578 --> 00:54:52,162
- Who are you?
- It's okay. Rachel. Rachel, it's all right.

740
00:54:52,247 --> 00:54:54,748
Let me go! No!

741
00:54:56,417 --> 00:54:58,544
- Rachel, it's okay.
- Look at me, look at me.

742
00:55:01,840 --> 00:55:04,758
I'm sorry about that.
I didn't want to interrupt.

743
00:55:04,843 --> 00:55:07,177
